Macedonians vote in referendum on whether to change the country's name
Macedonians voted Sunday in a referendum on whether to change the country's name to "Republic of North Macedonia", which would resolve a decades-old dispute with Greece that has blocked applications for membership in the European Union and NATO.
Greece has a province called Macedonia, and claims that the name of its northern neighbor represents a claim to its territory, and therefore has vetoed Macedonia's entry into NATO and the EU.
Both governments reached an agreement on the proposed new name in June, but nationalist opponents argue that the change will weaken the ethnic identity of the majority Slavic population in Macedonia.
President Gjorge Ivanov has said he will not vote in the referendum, and a campaign calling for a boycott has raised doubts about whether the required minimum of 50 percent of voters will turn out to make the referendum valid.
The question in the referendum was: 'Are you for NATO and EU membership with the acceptance of an agreement with Greece?'
Supporters of the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, argue that it is a price worth paying for Macedonia, one of the successor countries of the former Yugoslavia, to join organizations such as the EU and NATO.
"I came here today to vote for the future of the country, for the young people in Macedonia to live freely under the roof of the European Union, because it means a safer life for all of us", says 79-year-old Oliver Georgijevska from Skopje.
The referendum is not binding, but enough members of Parliament have said they will follow the result of the vote.
Changing the name would require a two-thirds majority in parliament.
The State Election Commission said there were no reports of any problems until 1 p.m.
However, the voter turnout was only 16 percent, compared to 34 percent in the last parliamentary elections in 2016, when 66 percent of registered voters eventually cast their ballots.
I went to vote for my children, our place is in Europe, says Gjose Tanevski, a 62-year-old voter from the capital Skopje.
Macedonian Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and son Dushko cast their votes in the Macedonian referendum on changing the name that would open the country to NATO and the European Union, in Strumica, Macedonia, on September 30, 2018.
In front of the Parliament in Skopje, Vladimir Kavardarkov, 54, prepares a small podium and pulls up chairs in front of tents erected by people boycotting the referendum.
"We are for NATO and the EU, but we want to enter them with our heads held high, not through the door for the servants", says Kavadarkov.
We are a poor country, but we have our pride.
If they don't want us to be like Macedonia, we can turn to others like China and Russia and become part of Eurasian integration.
Prime Minister Zaev says that NATO membership will bring much-needed investment to Macedonia, which has an unemployment rate of over 20%.
"I think a large majority will be in favour, because more than 80 percent of our citizens are in favour of the EU and NATO", Zaev said after voting.
The result of the election, he said, would be "a confirmation of our future".
According to a poll published last Monday by the Macedonian Institute for Policy Research, the turnout for the referendum could be between 30 and 43 percent of voters - which is less than the required turnout.
Another survey, conducted by the Macedonian broadcaster Telma TV, found that 57 percent of respondents planned to vote on Sunday.
Of those, 70% said they would vote yes.
For a referendum to be successful, it needs to be 50 percent plus one voter.
The referendum's failure would mark the first major blow to the pro-Western government's policy since it took office last May.
