Scottish Independent Schools have a history of academic success, and this continues in 2018 with further excellent exam results, as individual and group achievements in sports, arts, music and other community activities underline this.
These schools, with over 30,000 pupils across Scotland, are represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) and strive to provide the best possible service to their pupils and parents.
Independent schools prepare their students for further and higher education, their chosen careers, and their place as global citizens.
As an education sector that can design and implement individually tailored school curricula, we observe that modern languages are increasingly popular and in-demand subjects in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you talk to a man in a language he understands, it goes straight to his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, it goes straight to his heart.
The important point is that if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries, we can't rely on English alone.
The latest results from this year's examinations show that languages are at the top of the charts, with the independent schools not having the highest success rate.
A total of 68 percent of the students who took the foreign language course received the highest grades.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools show that 72 percent of Mandarin students, 72 percent of German students, 69 percent of French students, and 63 percent of Spanish students achieved the highest grade of A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland are promoting foreign languages as an important skill that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages as subjects of choice are given the same weight as STEM subjects in the curricula of independent and other schools.
A survey carried out by the UK's Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 found that 17 per cent of the reasons given by employers as being difficult to fill vacancies were due to insufficient language skills.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly becoming a necessity in preparing young people for their future careers.
As more and more jobs require languages, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Whatever career you choose, if you learn a second language, you will have a real advantage in the future, having a lifelong skill.
The ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries automatically gives a multilingual person an advantage over his or her competitors.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of 4,000 adults in the UK, 75 percent of them could not speak a foreign language well enough to carry on a conversation, with the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage of people, specifically 15 percent, being French.
That's why it's important for kids today to invest in language learning.
If children know more languages, especially those of emerging economies, they will have a better chance of finding meaningful employment.
In Scotland, each school differs in the languages it teaches.
Many schools focus on more classical modern languages, while others teach languages considered most important for the UK in the 2020 outlook, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the child's interests, he or she will always have a choice of several languages in independent schools with teachers who are experts in the field.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that prepares and equips children with the skills they need to succeed, whatever their future may hold.
At the moment, it is undeniable that languages are essential to the future of the country in a global business environment, so this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should be considered as 'international communication skills'.
