The course, which was introduced for the first time this year, provides students with basic information on how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance and improve their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and the university's executive director of health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after finding that students were really severely sleep deprived during the week.
The one-hour course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In one section, there's a picture of student halls where students click on coffee cups, curtains, sneakers, and books about the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is affected by lack of sleep and the importance of good sleep habits.
Another section tells participants how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons then invites participants to reflect on their daily routines.
We know that student behavior doesn't change immediately.
But we think they have a right to know - just as you have a right to know about the health effects of cigarette smoking,' added Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride in "studying all night" still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students meant that sleep deprivation was also a growing problem.
Getting good quality sleep should be a student's secret weapon to combat stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said - even to prevent weight gain, because sleep deprivation puts the brain in a starvation mode, so you're always hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old chemical and physical biology student from California, helped Professor Czeisler design a course that one of his Harvard freshman classes took last year.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to push for the whole course.
He hopes that the next step will be to ask all graduate students to complete a similar degree program before entering a competitive institution.
