German new warship delayed again
Germany's newest naval frigate was commissioned in 2014 to replace aging Cold War-era warships, but will be unavailable for at least another year due to faulty systems and a snowy coastline, local media reports.
The commissioning of the flagship Rheinland-Pfalz, a brand new Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigate, has now been postponed to the first half of 2019, according to the military spokesman quoted by Die Zeit.
The ship was scheduled to join the Navy in 2014, but difficult post-delivery issues have derailed the fate of this ambitious project.
The four Baden-Wuerttemberg class vessels, ordered by the Navy in 2007, will replace the aging Bremen-class frigates.
It is clear that they will be equipped with a high-powered cannon, a range of anti-aircraft and anti-ship ballistic missiles, and certain stealth technologies such as reduced radar and infrared and acoustic elements.
Other important features include long maintenance periods  it should be possible to deploy the latest frigates for up to two years out of home port.
But the continuous delays mean that the high-end naval vessels  that were supposed to enable Germany to send forces overseas  will be obsolete by the time they are commissioned, notes the daily Die Zeit.
The infamous F125 frigate made headlines last year when the German Navy officially refused to commission the vessel and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This was the first time the Navy had ever returned a ship to a manufacturer after a handover.
Little was known about the reasons for the return, but the German media cited a number of major "software bugs" and defects in the metal elements that would render the warship unusable in combat.
The software glitches were especially significant because the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class vessel will be operated by a crew of some 120 sailors  which is half the manpower needed on the Bremen-class frigates.
It has also been shown that the ship is significantly overweight, which reduces its performance and limits the Navy's ability to add future innovation.
It is believed that the 7,000-ton vessel Rheinland-Pfal will be twice as heavy as the ships of the same class used by the Germans during World War II.
Apart from the metallic component, the cost of the whole project, including crew training, is also a problem.
The original price of 2.2 billion euros is said to have risen to a staggering 3.1 billion euros.
The problems with the new frigates have become more significant in light of recent warnings that German naval power is declining.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German parliament's defense committee, confirmed that the navy was indeed "running out of deployable ships".
The representative stated that the problems had been compounded by the fact that old ships were being decommissioned but no replacements were provided.
He lamented that none of the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigates were capable of becoming part of the Navy's equipment.
The National Trust is listening to the secret lives of bats
A new study is being carried out at a bat colony in the Scottish Highlands to uncover how bats use the landscape to hunt for food.
It is hoped that the findings of the research will shed new light on the behavior of the unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation activities for the species.
The study, carried out by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland, will follow whistling and small-bodied bats and brown long-tailed and water bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in key areas of this bat colony to monitor bat activities throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also carry out mobile surveys using handheld detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all the recordings will determine the frequency of the bats' calls and what each species is doing.
A habitat map and report will be issued to create a detailed landscape picture of their behaviour.
Rob Dewar, a conservation adviser for the NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of habitat are most important to bats and how each species uses them.
This information will help to determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as grassland creation, and the best practice for maintaining wooded areas for bats and other related species.
The bat population in Scotland and across the UK has been declining dramatically over the last century.
They are threatened by development and land development that affect the colonies and natural environment.
Wind turbines and lighting may also pose a risk, as can fly traps and chemical treatments of building materials and cat attacks.
Bats aren't actually blind.
But because they hunt at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes.
They use sophisticated echo-location techniques to track bugs and obstacles in flight.
The NTS, responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens, and 76,000 acres of land in the country, takes bats very seriously.
It has trained specialists who regularly conduct surveys, inspections of colonies, and sometimes rescue work.
The organisation has even established the first and only dedicated bat reserve at Threave in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
The manager of the settlement, David Thompson, says that this is the ideal territory for them.
"We have a great area for bats here in Threave", he said.
We have old buildings, lots of ancient trees and the best habitat.
But there's still so much we don't know about bats, so the work we're doing here and elsewhere will help us better understand what they need to survive.
It highlights the importance of bat control before starting maintenance work in buildings, as it is possible that the unintentional destruction of one mother nest can kill up to 400 females and their young, which can destroy the entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, harass, disturb or destroy their colonies.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish representative of the Bat Conservation Trust, is encouraging the public to lend a hand in helping.
She said, "There's a lot to learn about our bats and a lot of species that we don't know about, how their populations are doing.
