Foreign buyers will be charged higher property tax when buying property in the UK
Foreign buyers will be charged a higher property tax when they buy property in the UK, with the money being used to help the homeless under the new Tory plans
This act will neutralize the success of Corbyn's move to attract young voters
Increased property tax liability for non-UK taxable persons
It is expected to increase the Treasury by £120 million a year to help the homeless
Foreign buyers will pay higher property tax when they buy property in the UK, with the extra money used to help the homeless, Theresa May announced today.
This action will be seen as an attempt to neutralize the success of Jeremy Corbyn's campaign to attract young voters with promises to provide more affordable housing and target high-income earners.
The property tax increase will affect individuals and businesses who don't pay taxes in the UK, with the extra money boosting the government's efforts to fight homelessness.
The surcharge, which is an addition to the current obligation to pay property purchase tax, including the higher rates introduced two years ago for second homes and purchases for rental purposes, can be as high as 3%.
It is estimated that the Treasury will increase its resources by up to £120 million a year.
Estimates say that 13 percent of London's newly built property is bought by non-UK residents, driving up prices and making it harder for first-time buyers to make it to the top of the home market.
Many of the country's rich areas - especially the capital - have become ghost towns because of the high number of foreign buyers who spend most of their time outside the country.
The new policy comes just weeks after Boris Johnson called for a property tax cut to help more young people own their first home.
He accused the big building firms of keeping property prices high by taking up land but not using it, and urged Mrs May to withdraw quotas from affordable housing to fix Britain's "housing shortage".
Mr Corbyn announced a compelling set of proposed housing reforms, including rent control and an end to forced evictions.
He also wants to give the committees more power to build new homes.
Mrs May said: 'Last year I said I wanted to dedicate my efforts as Prime Minister to rebuilding the British dream, so that each new generation can have a better life.
And that means fixing our broken property market.
Britain will always be open to people who want to live, work and make a life here.
But it can't be right that it should be easy for non-British residents and foreign companies to buy houses in the same way as hardworking British residents.
For many people, the dream of home is too far away, and the shame of sleeping without a roof over your head is too real.
