Here are some key facts about the city of Palu and the Donggala Regency on the island of Sulawesi:
Palu is the capital city of the province of Central Sulawesi, located at the end of a narrow bay on the west coast of Sulawesi Island, with an estimated population of 379,800 in 2017.
The city was just celebrating its 40th anniversary when an earthquake and tsunami struck.
Donggala is a regency stretching over 300 km (180 mi) along the coast of northwestern Sulawesi.
The Regency, an administrative region under the province, had a population of 299,200 in 2017.
The main components of the economy of Central Sulawesi are fishing and farming, especially in the coastal region of Donggala.
Nickel mining is also significant in the province, but is concentrated mainly in Morowali on the opposite coast of Sulawesi.
According to the Indonesian Disaster Mitigation Agency, Palu and Donggal have been hit by tsunamis several times in the past 100 years.
In 1938, the Donggale Tsunami killed over 200 people and destroyed hundreds of homes.
The tsunami that hit the western Donggala in 1996 also claimed nine lives.
Indonesia is located on the seismic Pacific Ring of Fire and regularly experiences earthquakes.
Here is a list of some of the biggest earthquakes and tsunamis in recent years:
2004: A major earthquake on the west coast of Indonesia's Aceh province in northern Sumatra on 26 December caused a tsunami that affected 14 countries and killed 226,000 people along the Indian Ocean coast, with more than half of those in Aceh province.
2005: A series of powerful earthquakes struck the west coast of Sumatra in late March and early April.
Hundreds died on Nias Island off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: A 6.8-magnitude earthquake hits the south of Indonesia's most populous island, Java, causing a tsunami that hits the southern coast, killing nearly 700 people.
2009: A 7.6-magnitude earthquake struck near Padang, the capital of the province of West Sumatra.
More than 1,100 people lost their lives.
2010: An earthquake of magnitude 7.5 struck one of the Mentawai Islands, near Sumatra, causing a 10-meter (32 ft) -high tsunami that destroyed dozens of villages and killed about 300 people.
2016: A light earthquake struck the Pidie Jaya regency in Aceh Province, causing destruction and panic as people were reminded of the devastating effects of the deadly 2004 earthquake and tsunami.
This time, no tsunami formed, but more than 100 died from collapsing buildings.
2018: A powerful earthquake struck the Indonesian tourist island of Lombok, killing more than 500 people, mostly on the northern side of the island.
The earthquake destroyed thousands of buildings and left thousands of tourists temporarily trapped.
